            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XVIII.R6</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Drooping Downward</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-991a5335-7fff-595b-f86c-430208545726\"><br />This note picks up language from the left-hand notes for the previous installment, No. XVII: &ldquo;Clennam going downward?&rdquo; (LD.XVII.L4). The chapter notes for this number will repeat the refrain below: &ldquo;Ever downward, always downward&rdquo; (LD.XVIII.R14). Dickens echoes this language in descriptions of Arthur&rsquo;s spirit in the opening of the <em>next</em> chapter (&ldquo;the weight under which he bent was hearing him down&rdquo; &ldquo;down in the despondency of a low, slow fever&rdquo; [LD 733-734]). As it applies to <em>this</em> chapter, the note summarizes Clennam&rsquo;s despondency, especially as it is described in the opening paragraphs: &ldquo;Anybody might see that the shadow of the wall was dark upon him&rdquo; (715).</span></p>",
            "format": "text/html"
        }
